    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Broker in South Asia</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Abdul Rehman letter says new US closeness with India should not be at expense of longtime ally Pakistan, and US should try to preserve its role as impartial broker on volatile issue of Kashmir (Sept 20 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A 'Tilt' Toward India'' (editorial, Sept. 20):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A 'Tilt' Toward India'' (editorial, Sept. 20):</p>
        <p>Our new closeness with India does not have to be at the expense of our longtime ally Pakistan. With their fingers on the nuclear trigger, both Pakistan and India must be regarded as true nuclear powers, and it is in our interest to see strong and stable governments in both of these countries.</p>
        <p>We must share some responsibility for the current political and economic environment of Pakistan, in the aftermath of its experience with the Soviet Union and Afghanistan. We should also try to preserve our role as an impartial broker in any future discussions between these two countries on the volatile issue of Kashmir.</p>
        <p>ABDUL REHMAN  Staten Island, Sept. 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
